{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480655"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:48:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:48:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"91"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"91","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/91"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.06,0.51,0.07,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"91"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104426"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"91","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/91"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"91"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86751"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"100"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1875"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2665"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5002"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12732"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5040"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41987"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45004"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104426"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old Indigenous woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a regular check-up. She has a history of rheumatic heart disease, dyslipidaemia, and is a current smoker with a 40 pack-year history. Her regular medications include atorvastatin. She has no allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 80/min and irregularly irregular, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals a loud first heart sound with an opening snap and a rumbling mid-diastolic murmur heard best in expiration with the patient in the left lateral position. An electrocardiogram confirms newly-identified atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate anticoagulant for long-term thromboprophylaxis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Apixaban","Aspirin","Warfarin","No anticoagulation","Rivaroxaban"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has valvular atrial fibrillation (AF) due to rheumatic mitral stenosis, evidenced by the classic examination findings of a loud first heart sound, opening snap, and mid-diastolic murmur. Valvular AF is commonly defined as AF arising in the setting of haemodynamically significant mitral stenosis or in the presence of mechanical prosthetic heart valve(s), because each of these confer a significantly increased thromboembolic risk when compared to non-valvular AF. As a result, anticoagulation is essentially always indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is the only appropriate anticoagulant for valvular AF. All major trials of direct oral anticoagulants excluded patients with significant mitral stenosis or mechanical heart valves. The RE-ALIGN trial showed increased adverse events with direct oral anticoagulants in patients with mechanical valves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban\u003C/strong\u003E and other direct oral anticoagulants are contraindicated in valvular AF. While they are preferred over warfarin in non-valvular AF due to reduced bleeding risk and no need for monitoring, their safety and efficacy have not been established in valvular AF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inadequate for stroke prevention in AF, particularly in high-risk patients with valvular disease. It provides minimal protection against thromboembolism compared to anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo anticoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the very high risk of thromboembolism in valvular AF. The presence of mitral stenosis mandates anticoagulation regardless of other risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E, like other direct oral anticoagulants, is contraindicated in valvular AF due to lack of evidence for safety and efficacy in this population.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Warfarin is the anticoagulant of choice in valvular atrial fibrillation where there is evidence of mitral stenosis.","Direct oral anticoagulants are contraindicated in valvular atrial fibrillation.","Clinical features of mitral stenosis include loud S1, opening snap, and mid-diastolic murmur best heard in left lateral position during expiration."],"references":["Lip et al. Antithrombotic therapy in atrial fibrillation associated with valvular heart disease: a joint consensus document from the European Heart Rhythm Association (EHRA) and European Society of Cardiology Working Group on Thrombosis. Europace. 2017 Nov 1;19(11):1757-1758.","Otto CM, Nishimura RA, Bonow RO et al. 2020 ACC/AHA Guideline for the Management of Patients With Valvular Heart Disease: Executive Summary. Circulation 2021; 143:e35-e71.","Ralph AP, Noonan S, Wade V, Currie BJ. The 2020 Australian guideline for prevention, diagnosis and management of acute rheumatic fever and rheumatic heart disease. Med J Aust. 2021;214(5):220-227. doi:10.5694/mja2.50851"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86751"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"91"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86751"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T08:39:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T08:42:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"91"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104426"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"